  "text": "It has been shown previously that the activation of MVspecific CD4 ϩ T cells in spleens of resistant mice correlates with low virus titers in brain tissue, resulting in lack of clinical signs and protection [CITATION_1] . In contrast, a lack of MV-specific CD4 ϩ T-cell proliferation in spleens of susceptible mice correlates with high virus titers in brain tissue and death [CITATION_2] . Therefore, the neutralization of IFN-␥ inhibits MHC-II-dependent antigen presentation and subsequent proliferation of CD4 ϩ T cells, resulting in breakdown of resistance. In mice with a deletion in the IFN-␥ gene, the primary immune response toward measles is also affected by the lack of IFN-␥ because all IFN-␥ Ϫ/Ϫ mice die after MV infection with faster kinetics than those of IFN-␥ ϩ/ϩ control mice (data not shown). However, in the secondary immune response T-cell proliferation is comparable to that for IFN-␥ ϩ/ϩ mice (Table   FIG. ) into IFN-␥ Ϫ/Ϫ mice protects against encephalitis. This demonstrates that the influence of IFN-␥ on antigen presentation is overcome during the secondary immune response in these animals. It seems to be obvious that the constant lack of IFN-␥ in these animals has led to so far unknown adaptations in antigen processing. In contrast, in animals with an intact genome the neutralization of IFN-␥ inhibits antigen processing and T-cell proliferation. APC. In addition, either recombinant IFN-␥ (2.5 pg/ml) or IFN-␥-neutralizing antibodies (12.5 g/ml) were added. The differences in the SI with and without the addition of recombinant IFN-␥ were significant (P Ͻ 0.05, Kruskal-Wallis test), as were the differences with and without neutralizing antibody (P Ͻ 0.05, t test) (error bars indicate standard deviations). The lack of IFN-␥ did not reduce constitutive MHC-II expression on APC, whereas the addition of IFN-␥ increased it (data not shown). Concanavalin A-dependent proliferation was not influenced by the lack or addition of IFN-␥ (data not shown). In addition, concanavalin A-dependent proliferation of spleen cells from naive animals was not influenced by IFN-␥ concentrations ranging from 40 ng to 0.04 pg/ml (data not shown). (b) BALB/c mice were infected i.c. with 5 ϫ 10 4 TCID 50 of MV strain CAM/RBH and injected daily with IFN-␥-neutralizing antibodies (black bars) or left untreated (striped bars). On days 4, 5, and 6, MV-specific T-cell proliferation was measured from spleen cells (error bars indicate standard deviations). The levels of proliferation of spleen cells from these animals after concanavalin A stimulation were comparable (data not shown).",
